# Python Telegram bot

## Application shape

- Build `Application` in `bot/main.py`. Put shared objects on `application.bot_data` (e.g. `orchestrator`, `admin_chat_id`).
- Register handlers with `CommandHandler`. New commands: add handler in `main.py`, implement async handler in `bot/handlers.py`.

## Handlers

- Handlers are `async`. Use `context.bot_data` for `Orchestrator` and admin id — not globals.
- **Admin-only**: reuse `_deny_if_not_admin` / `_admin_id` pattern from `bot/handlers.py` for any privileged command (gate compares `update.effective_user.id` to `bot_data["admin_chat_id"]`, i.e. the configured admin **user** id).

## Separation of concerns

- **Handlers**: Telegram I/O, call `Orchestrator` or small helpers.
- **Orchestrator** (`orchestrator.py`): ordering, `peek_next_item` / `record_delivered`, `status_text`, manifest reload via `load_content`.
- **Parsing / validation**: `schemas.py`, `content_loader.py` — do not duplicate manifest rules in handlers.

## Manifest item types

- Queue items include **`poll`** (Telegram quiz), not only text/photo/document. Poll items may carry **`theme_note`** (English follow-up message after the quiz). Extend `schemas.py` / handlers together when changing manifest shape.

## Optional hooks

- `schedule_next_delivery` in `orchestrator.py` is a no-op stub; daily timing uses `JobQueue` in `bot/main.py` when `ENABLE_SCHEDULED_POSTING` is set.

## Quality assurance

- After substantive changes to handlers, orchestrator, schemas, `content_loader`, `state_store`, or `config.py`, run `pytest` from the repo root (install [requirements-dev.txt](../../requirements-dev.txt) first). Add or extend tests in `tests/` when behavior changes.
